INSERT INTO `category` (`id`, `name`, `description`) VALUES
(1, 'Ammunition', 'Ammunition refers to the projectiles used by ranged weapons. This category encompasses items like arrows for bows, bolts for crossbows, sling bullets for slings, and sometimes specialized projectiles like rocks or darts.  Ammunition is consumed when used, meaning that characters need to acquire and manage their supply.  The type of ammunition used can sometimes affect the damage dealt or other properties of the ranged attack.  While some ranged weapons, like thrown daggers, don\'t strictly use \"ammunition\" in the same way, the term generally refers to the expendable projectiles necessary for most ranged weaponry.'),
(2, 'Arcane focus', 'An Arcane Focus is a specialized tool used by spellcasters, particularly wizards, sorcerers, warlocks, and sometimes bards, to channel their arcane energies when casting spells.  It acts as a tangible representation of their magical power and helps them manipulate the Weave of magic.  Arcane foci can take many forms, such as wands, staves, orbs, crystals, or even specially crafted amulets or rods.  While not strictly required for all spells (some spells have material components that are consumed instead), an arcane focus can often substitute for the material components of a spell if those components don\'t have a specific cost listed.  Using an arcane focus is not the same as providing the material components; it simply allows the caster to bypass the need for those components if they lack a specific gold piece value.  It\'s an important piece of equipment for many spellcasters, both functionally and often as a symbol of their magical abilities.'),
(3, 'Artisan\'s tools', 'Artisan\'s Tools are specialized kits containing the instruments and materials necessary for practicing a specific craft or trade.  This category encompasses a wide variety of tools, such as alchemist\'s supplies, brewer\'s supplies, calligrapher\'s supplies, carpenter\'s tools, cobbler\'s tools, cook\'s utensils, glassblower\'s tools, jeweler\'s tools, leatherworker\'s tools, mason\'s tools, painter\'s supplies, potter\'s tools, smith\'s tools, tinker\'s tools, weaver\'s tools, and woodcarver\'s tools.  Proficiency with a set of artisan\'s tools allows a character to create items related to that craft, perform repairs, or contribute to other relevant tasks.  These tools are essential for characters with crafting backgrounds or those who wish to engage in crafting during downtime.  They can also be used to add flavor and detail to roleplaying scenarios.'),
(4, 'Clothes', 'Clothes can be defined as wearable items not primarily intended for combat or magical protection.  This category encompasses items used for social status, disguise, comfort, utility, and aesthetics, ranging from common tunics and trousers to fine gowns and specialized garb like scholar\'s robes or performer\'s outfits.  Clothing choices reveal character background and personality, influencing social interactions and potentially affecting skill checks.  The cost and availability of clothing vary based on quality and location, adding depth to the game world and enriching roleplaying opportunities by allowing players to express their characters through their attire.'),
(5, 'Container', 'Containers are items designed to hold and transport other objects. This category encompasses a wide range of vessels, from simple pouches and sacks to elaborate chests and locked strongboxes.  Containers serve practical purposes like organizing gear, concealing valuables, and managing encumbrance.  Their size and construction influence their carrying capacity, durability, and security.  Containers can be mundane, like a leather waterskin or a wooden chest, or more specialized, such as a wizard\'s component pouch or a thief\'s lockpicks case.  The contents of a container are typically tracked separately, adding a layer of inventory management to the game, and the security of a container, whether through locks or hidden compartments, can be a factor in adventures.'),
(6, 'Druidic focus', 'A Druidic Focus is a tool used by druids to channel their connection to nature when casting spells.  It\'s a tangible object that represents their attunement to the natural world and helps them manipulate the forces of nature.  Druidic foci can take various forms, such as a sprig of mistletoe or holly, a wand or scepter made of yew or another special wood, a staff drawn whole out of a living tree, or a totem object incorporating natural elements like feathers, fur, bones, and teeth.  Like an arcane focus for other spellcasters, a druidic focus can often substitute for the material components of a spell if those components don\'t have a specific cost listed.  It\'s an essential item for druids, both as a functional tool for their magic and as a symbol of their connection to the wild.'),
(7, 'Gaming set', 'This item encompasses a wide range of game pieces, including dice and decks of cards (for games such as Three-Dragon Ante). A few common examples appear on the Tools table, but other kinds of gaming sets exist. If you are proficient with a gaming set, you can add your proficiency bonus to ability checks you make to play a game with that set. Each type of gaming set requires a separate proficiency.'),
(8, 'Heavy armor', 'Heavy Armor is a category of armor designed to provide significant protection in combat.  It is the most protective of the nonmagical armor types, offering a high Armor Class (AC) bonus.  However, heavy armor is also the most cumbersome, imposing penalties on movement and stealth.  Characters wearing heavy armor have disadvantage on Stealth checks, and it often has Strength requirements to avoid further penalties.  Examples of heavy armor include chain mail, splint, and plate armor.  While offering excellent defense, heavy armor\'s drawbacks make it less suitable for characters prioritizing agility or stealth.'),
(9, 'Holy symbol', 'A \"Holy Symbol\" is a sacred object used by clerics, paladins, and sometimes other divine spellcasters to channel divine power and perform miracles.  It serves as a tangible representation of their faith and connection to their deity or divine source.  Holy symbols can take many forms, such as a pendant, amulet, reliquary, or even a symbol etched onto a shield or weapon.  They are often associated with a specific deity or pantheon and may bear their insignia or representational image.  Like an arcane or druidic focus, a holy symbol can often substitute for the material components of a spell if those components don\'t have a specific cost listed.  It\'s an essential item for divine spellcasters, both for its functional use in spellcasting and as a symbol of their devotion.'),
(10, 'Kit', 'A \"Kit\" is a collection of tools and supplies designed for a specific purpose.  Unlike individual tools or artisan\'s tools which are often focused on crafting, kits are more geared toward specific activities or situations.  Examples include an alchemist\'s kit (for brewing potions and concoctions), a burglar\'s pack (for lockpicking and other thievery), a climber\'s kit (for scaling walls and cliffs), a healer\'s kit (for treating wounds and ailments), or a mess kit (for preparing food).  Kits often provide a bonus or advantage when used for their intended purpose, reflecting the convenience and efficiency of having the right tools gathered together.  They streamline certain tasks and are often essential for characters specializing in particular skills or professions.'),
(11, 'Light armor', 'Light Armor is a category of armor that offers basic protection while allowing for greater mobility and flexibility compared to heavier armor types.  Light armor is typically made from supple and lightweight materials like leather or padded cloth. It provides a lower Armor Class (AC) bonus than medium or heavy armor, but it allows the wearer to add their Dexterity modifier to their AC, making it a good choice for agile characters.  Examples of light armor include padded armor, leather armor, and studded leather armor.  Light armor is often favored by rogues, rangers, and other classes that prioritize mobility and stealth.'),
(12, 'Martial Melee Weapon', 'Martial Melee Weapons are weapons designed for close-quarters combat, requiring specific training to wield effectively. This category distinguishes them from simple weapons and ranged weapons. Martial melee weapons encompass a variety of bladed, blunt, and pole-based implements, including swords, axes, hammers, spears, and polearms. They typically deal more damage than simple weapons and sometimes possess special properties like reach or the ability to be used two-handed. Proficiency with a martial melee weapon is often tied to specific classes or feats, reflecting a character\'s combat training.  These weapons are fundamental tools for adventurers, influencing combat tactics and character build choices.'),
(13, 'Martial Ranged Weapon', 'Martial Ranged Weapons are ranged weapons requiring specialized training to use effectively, setting them apart from simple ranged weapons. This category includes weapons like longbows, heavy crossbows, and slings, often dealing significant damage and sometimes possessing properties like increased range or the need for two hands.  Proficiency with martial ranged weapons is usually tied to specific classes or feats, reflecting a character\'s combat training. These weapons are crucial for characters who prefer to engage enemies from a distance, offering tactical advantages in combat.'),
(14, 'Martial Weapon', 'Martial Weapons are a category of weapons that require specialized training to use effectively. This category encompasses both melee and ranged weapons, generally dealing more damage than simple weapons and sometimes possessing special properties.  Proficiency with martial weapons is often tied to specific classes or feats, reflecting a character\'s combat training.  Martial weapons are more complex and diverse than simple weapons, offering a wider range of options for adventurers.  Examples include longswords, great axes, handaxes, scimitars, rapiers, whips (melee), longbows, heavy crossbows, and nets (ranged). They are essential tools for many adventurers, significantly influencing combat tactics and character build choices.'),
(15, 'Medium armor', 'Medium Armor is a category of armor that balances protection and mobility.  It offers a higher Armor Class (AC) bonus than light armor but is less cumbersome than heavy armor.  Medium armor is typically made from materials like hide, chainmail, or scale mail.  It allows the wearer to add their Dexterity modifier to their AC, up to a maximum of +2.  This makes it a good choice for characters who want decent protection without sacrificing too much agility. Examples of medium armor include hide armor, chain shirt, scale mail, and breastplate.  Many classes, such as clerics, bards, and some fighters, find medium armor to be a suitable compromise between defense and maneuverability.'),
(16, 'Melee Weapon', 'Melee Weapon is any weapon designed for use in close combat, where the wielder is typically within striking distance of their target.  This category encompasses a wide variety of implements, including swords, axes, hammers, spears, and polearms.  Melee weapons are used to make melee attacks, which are resolved using Strength for most weapons (or Dexterity for finesse weapons).  They are a fundamental tool for many classes, and the choice of melee weapon can significantly impact a character\'s combat style and effectiveness.  Melee weapons are distinct from ranged weapons, which are designed for attacking at a distance.'),
(17, 'Misc', 'A catch-all category for items that don\'t neatly fit into other classifications.  It\'s a broad category encompassing a wide range of objects that might be found during adventures, purchased from merchants, or crafted by players.  \"Misc\" items can include anything from mundane tools like crowbars and shovels, to unusual trinkets, strange artifacts, or unidentifiable objects of unknown purpose.  These items often serve as props for roleplaying, clues in investigations, or rewards for completing quests.  While they may not always have immediate mechanical benefits, misc items can add flavor and depth to the game world, sparking creativity and driving the narrative forward.  Their value and purpose can vary greatly, often depending on the specific context of the adventure.'),
(18, 'Mixture', 'Mixtures are alchemically created substances with varying effects, distinct from potions or other magical items.  This category encompasses a broad range of concoctions, from volatile explosives and potent poisons to helpful concoctions like fast-drying glue or smokepowder.  Mixtures are often created using alchemist\'s supplies and require specific recipes or formulas. Their effects can be immediate or delayed, and they may have varying degrees of potency or stability.  Unlike potions, mixtures are not inherently magical, relying instead on chemical reactions and the properties of their ingredients.  They add an element of unpredictability and creativity to gameplay, offering both opportunities and risks depending on their use.'),
(19, 'Musical instrument', 'Musical Instrument is an item used to create music. This category encompasses a wide variety of instruments, from simple drums and flutes to complex harps and lutes.  Musical instruments are often used by bards to cast spells, perform for audiences, or provide background music for storytelling and roleplaying.  They can also be used by other classes for entertainment, skill checks involving Performance, or even as tools for distraction or communication.  The quality and type of instrument can influence its cost and effectiveness in performances.  Musical instruments add flavor and cultural richness to the game world, offering opportunities for characters to express themselves creatively and interact with others through music.'),
(20, 'Pack', 'A \"Pack\" is a pre-assembled collection of gear and supplies designed for a specific purpose or profession.  It\'s a convenient way to acquire essential equipment without having to purchase each item individually.  Packs often contain a variety of useful items, such as tools, rations, clothing, and other necessities, bundled together at a generally reasonable price.  Examples include an adventurer\'s pack (containing basic adventuring gear), a burglar\'s pack (for thievery), a diplomat\'s pack (for social encounters), or a scholar\'s pack (for research and study).  Packs streamline the process of equipping characters, especially at lower levels, and provide a thematic set of items appropriate for their background or chosen profession.  While the contents of a pack are fixed, players can often add or remove items as needed.'),
(21, 'Ranged Weapon', 'Ranged Weapon is any weapon designed for attacking targets at a distance.  This category includes a variety of implements, such as bows, crossbows, slings, and thrown weapons.  Ranged weapons allow characters to engage enemies without entering melee combat, offering a tactical advantage.  Attacks with ranged weapons are typically resolved using Dexterity.  The range of a ranged weapon determines how far it can effectively reach, and different ranged weapons have varying damage dice and other properties.  Ranged weapons are a crucial tool for many classes, particularly those specializing in ranged combat. They are distinct from melee weapons, which are designed for close-quarters fighting.'),
(22, 'Shield', 'A \"Shield\" is a piece of defensive equipment designed to be held in one hand or strapped to the forearm to deflect blows and provide additional protection in combat.  Shields grant a bonus to Armor Class (AC), making the wielder harder to hit.  They are typically made of wood or metal and come in various sizes, offering different levels of protection.  Using a shield often requires proficiency, and some shields may have specific restrictions or requirements.  While providing a significant defensive benefit, shields typically occupy a hand, limiting the wielder\'s ability to use two-handed weapons or perform certain actions.  They are a common and effective way for characters to increase their survivability in combat.'),
(23, 'Simple Melee Weapon', 'Simple Melee Weapons are basic, readily available weapons requiring minimal training to use effectively. This category includes common implements like clubs, daggers, quarterstaffs, and sickles. They are generally less expensive and deal less damage than martial weapons.  Simple melee weapons are often the starting weapons for many characters and are accessible to most classes without requiring specific proficiencies.  While not as powerful as martial weapons, they are reliable and versatile, serving as essential tools for adventurers in various situations.'),
(24, 'Simple Ranged Weapon', 'Simple Ranged Weapons are basic ranged weapons requiring minimal training to use effectively. This category includes common implements like darts, slings, and light crossbows. They are generally less expensive and deal less damage than martial ranged weapons. Simple ranged weapons are often accessible to most classes without requiring specific proficiencies and serve as a basic option for characters who prefer to attack from a distance. While not as powerful as martial ranged weapons, they are readily available and can be effective in certain situations.'),
(25, 'Simple Weapon', 'Simple Weapons are a category of readily available and easy-to-use implements for combat.  This category includes both melee and ranged weapons, requiring minimal training to wield effectively.  Simple weapons are generally less expensive and deal less damage than martial weapons.  They are often the starting weapons for many characters and are accessible to most classes without requiring specific proficiencies.  Examples of simple weapons include clubs, daggers, quarterstaffs, sickles, darts, slings, and light crossbows. While not as powerful as martial weapons, simple weapons are versatile and reliable, serving as essential tools for adventurers in various situations.'),
(26, 'Toxin', 'Toxins are substances designed to inflict harmful effects when ingested, inhaled, absorbed through the skin, or injected. This category encompasses a wide range of poisons, venoms, and other noxious substances, each with varying degrees of potency, onset time, and specific effects.  Toxins can be natural, derived from plants or animals, or artificially created. They can be used to incapacitate, weaken, or even kill a creature.  The resistance to a toxin, often determined by a Constitution saving throw, is crucial to surviving its effects.  Toxins play a significant role in the game, appearing in traps, encountered on creatures, and sometimes wielded by villains or even adventurers, adding an element of danger and intrigue to the game.'),
(27, 'Venom', 'Venom is a specific type of toxin produced by certain creatures, often as a means of defense or hunting.  While all venoms are toxins, not all toxins are venoms.  Venoms are typically delivered through bites, stings, or other natural weapons of the creature that produces them.  They often have specific effects tailored to the creature\'s needs, such as paralyzing prey, inflicting pain, or causing rapid tissue necrosis.  The potency and effects of a venom vary greatly depending on the creature.  Overcoming a venom\'s effects usually requires a Constitution saving throw, and failure can result in debilitating conditions or even death.  Venoms are a common threat, adding a layer of danger to encounters with venomous creatures.');
INSERT INTO `class` (`id`, `name`, `description`, `hit_die`, `abilities`, `max_skills`, `tools`, `initial_funding_dice`, `initial_funding_multiplier`, `initial_funding_coin`) VALUES
(1, 'Barbarian', 'A tall human tribesman strides through a blizzard, draped in fur and hefting his axe. He laughs as he charges toward the frost giant who dared poach his people\'s elk herd. A half-orc snarls at the latest challenger to her authority over their savage tribe, ready to break his neck with her bare hands as she did to the last six rivals. Frothing at the mouth, a dwarf slams his helmet into the face of his drow foe, then turns to drive his armored elbow into the gut of another. These barbarians, different as they might be, are defined by their rage: unbridled, unquenchable, and unthinking fury. More than a mere emotion, their anger is the ferocity of a cornered predator, the unrelenting assault of a storm, the churning turmoil of the sea. For some, their rage springs from a communion with fierce animal spirits. Others draw from a roiling reservoir of anger at a world full of pain. For every barbarian, rage is a power that fuels not just a battle frenzy but also uncanny reflexes, resilience, and feats of strength.', '1d12', 1, 2, 0, '2d4', 10, 'gp'),
(2, 'Bard', 'Humming as she traces her fingers over an ancient monument in a long-forgotten ruin, a half-elf in rugged leathers finds knowledge springing into her mind, conjured forth by the magic of her song-knowledge of the people who constructed the monument and the mythic saga it depicts. A stern human warrior bangs his sword rhythmically against his scale mail, setting the tempo for his war chant and exhorting his companions to bravery and heroism. The magic of his song fortifies and emboldens them. Laughing as she tunes her cittern, a gnome weaves her subtle magic over the assembled nobles, ensuring that her companions\' words will be well received. Whether scholar, skald, or scoundrel, a bard weaves magic through words and music to inspire allies, demoralize foes, manipulate minds, create illusions, and even heal wounds.', '1d8', 1, 3, 3, '5d4', 10, 'gp'),
(3, 'Cleric', 'Arms and eyes upraised toward the sun and a prayer on his lips, an elf begins to glow with an inner light that spills out to heal his battle-worn companions. Chanting a song of glory, a dwarf swings his axe in wide swaths to cut through the ranks of orcs arrayed against him, shouting praise to the gods with every foe\'s fall. Calling down a curse upon the forces of undeath, a human lifts her holy symbol as light pours from it to drive back the zombies crowding in on her companions. Clerics are intermediaries between the mortal world and the distant planes of the gods. As varied as the gods they serve, clerics strive to embody the handiwork of their deities. No ordinary priest, a cleric is imbued with divine magic.', '1d8', 1, 2, 0, '5d4', 10, 'gp'),
(4, 'Druid', 'Holding high a gnarled staff wreathed with holly, an elf summons the fury of the storm and calls down explosive bolls of lightning to smile the torch-carrying orcs who threaten her forest. Crouching out of sight on a high tree branch in the form of a leopard, a human peers out of the jungle at the strange construction of a temple of Evil Elemental Air, keeping a close eye on the cultists\' activities, Swinging a blade formed of pure fire, a half-elf charges into a mass of skeletal soldiers, sundering the unnatural magic that gives the foul creatures the mocking semblance of life. Whether calling on the elemental forces of nature or emulating the creatures of the animal world, druids are an embodiment of nature\'s resilience, cunning, and fury. They claim no mastery over nature. Instead, they see themselves as extensions of nature\'s indomitable will.', '1d8', 1, 2, 1, '2d4', 10, 'gp'),
(5, 'Fighter', 'A human in clanging plate armor holds her shield before her as she runs toward the massed goblins. An elf behind her, clad in studded leather armor, peppers the goblins with arrows loosed from his exquisite bow. The half-orc nearby shouts orders, helping the two combatants coordinate their assault to the best advantage. A dwarf in chain mail interposes his shield between the ogre\'s club and his companion, knocking the deadly blow aside. His companion, a half-elf in scale armor, swings two scimitars in a blinding whirl as she circles the ogre, looking for a blind spot in its defenses. A gladiator fights for sport in an arena, a master with his trident and net, skilled at toppling foes and moving them around for the crowd\'s delight-and his own tactical advantage. His opponent\'s sword flares with blue light an instant before she sends lightning flashing forth to smite him. Ali of these heroes are fighters, perhaps the most diverse class of characters in the worlds of DUNGEONS & DRAGONS. Questing knights, conquering overlords, royal champions, elite foot soldiers, hardened mercenaries, and bandit kings-as fighters, they all share an unparalleled mastery with weapons and armor, and a thorough knowledge of the skills of combat. And they are well acquainted with death, both meting it out and staring it defiantly in the face.', '1d10', 1, 2, 0, '5d4', 10, 'gp'),
(6, 'Monk', 'Her fists a blur as they detect an incoming hail of arrows, a half-elf springs over a barricade and throws herself into the massed ranks of hobgoblins on the other side. She whirls among them. knocking their blows aside and sending them reeling. until at last she stands alone. Taking a deep breath. a human covered in tattoos settles into a battle stance. As the first charging orcs reach him. he exhales and a blast of tire roars from his mouth, engulfing his foes. Moving with the silence of the night, a black-clad halfling steps into a shadow beneath an arch and emerges from another inky shadow on a balcony a stone\'s throw away. She slides her blade free of its cloth-wrapped scabbard and peers through the open window at the tyrant prince. so vulnerable in the grip of sleep. Whatever their discipline, monks are united in their ability to magically harness the energy that flows in their bodies. Whether channeled as a striking display of combat prowess or a subtler focus of defensive ability and speed, this energy infuses all that a monk does.', '1d8', 2, 2, 1, '5d4', 1, 'gp'),
(7, 'Paladin', 'Clad in plate armor that gleams in the sunlight despite the dust and grime of long travel, a human lays down her sword and shield and places her hands on a mortally wounded mano Divine radiance shines from her hands, the man\'s wounds knit closed, and his eyes open wide with amazement. A dwarf crouches behind an outcrop, his black cloak making him nearly invisible in the night, and watches an orc war band celebrating its recent victory. Silently, he stalks into their midst and whispers an oath, and two orcs are dead before they even realize he is there. Silver hair shining in a shaft of light that seems to illuminate only him, an elf laughs with exultation. His spear flashes like his eyes as he jabs again and again at a twisted giant, until at last his light overcomes its hideous darkness. Whatever their origin and their mission, paladins are united by their oaths to stand against the forces of evil. Whether sworn before a god\'s altar and the witness of a priest, in a sacred glade before nature spirits and fey beings, or in a moment of desperation and grief with the dead as the only witness, a paladin\'s oath is a powerful bond. It is a source of power that turns a devout warrior into a blessed champion.', '1d10', 2, 2, 0, '5d4', 10, 'gp'),
(8, 'Ranger', 'Rough and wild looking, a human stalks alone through the shadows of trees, hunting the orcs he knows are planning a raid on a nearby farm, Clutching a shortsword in each hand, he becomes a whirlwind of steel, cutting down one enemy after another. After tumbling away from a cone of freezing air, an elf finds her feet and draws back her bow to loose an arrow at the white dragon. Shrugging off the wave of fear that emanates from the dragon like the cold of its breath, she sends one arrow after another to find the gaps between the dragon\'s thick scales. Holding his hand high, a half-elf whistles to the hawk that circles high above him, calling the bird back to his side. Whispering instructions in Elvish, he points to the owlbear he\'s been tracking and sends the hawk to distract the creature while he readies his bow. Far from the bustle of cities and towns, past the hedges that shelter the most distant farms from the terrors of the wild, amid the dense-packed trees of trackless forests and across wide and empty plains, rangers keep their unending watch.', '1d10', 2, 3, 0, '5d4', 10, 'gp'),
(9, 'Rogue', 'Signaling for her companions to wait, a halfling creeps forward through the dungeon hall. She presses an ear to the door, then pulls out a set of tools and picks the lock in the blink of an eye. Then she disappears into the shadows as her fighter friend moves forward to kick the door open. A human lurks in the shadows of an alley while his accomplice prepares for her part in the ambush. When their target-a notorious slaver-passes the alleyway, the accomplice cries out, the slaver comes to investigate, and the assassin\'s blade cuts his throat before he can make a sound. Suppressing a giggle, a gnome waggles her fingers and magically lifts the key ring from the guard\'s belt. In a moment, the keys are in her hand, the cell door is open, and she and her companions are free to make their escape. Rogues rely on skill, stealth, and their foes\' vulnerabilities to get the upper hand in any situation. They have a knack for finding the solution to just about any problem, demonstrating a resourcefulness and versatility that is the cornerstone of any successful adventuring party.', '1d8', 1, 4, 1, '4d4', 10, 'gp'),
(10, 'Sorcerer', 'Golden eyes flashing, a human stretches out her hand and unleashes the dragonfire that burns in her veins. As an inferno rages around her foes, leathery wings spread from her back and she takes to the air. Long hair whipped by a conjured wind, a half-elf spreads his arms wide and throws his head back. Lifting him momentarily off the ground. a wave of magic surges up in him, through him, and out from him in a mighty blast of lightning. Crouching behind a stalagmite, a halfling points a finger at a charging troglodyte. A blast of fire springs from her finger to strike the creature. She ducks back behind the rock formation with a grin, unaware that her wild magic has turned her skin bright blue. Sorcerers carry a magical birthright conferred upon them by an exotic bloodline, some otherworldly influence. or exposure to unknown cosmic forces. One can\'t study sorcery as one learns a language, any more than one can learn to live a legendary life. No one chooses sorcery; the power chooses the sorcerer.', '1d6', 1, 2, 0, '3d4', 10, 'gp'),
(11, 'Warlock', 'With a pseudodragon curled on his shoulder, a young elf in golden robes smiles warmly, weaving a magical charm into his honeyed words and bending the palace sentinel to his will. As flames spring to life in her hands, a wizened human whispers the secret name of her demonic patron, infusing her spell with fiendish magic. Shifting his gaze between a battered tome and the odd alignment of the stars overhead, a wild-eyed tiefling chants the mystic ritual that will open a doorway to a distant world. Warlocks are seekers of the knowledge that lies hidden in the fabric of the multiverse. Through pacts made with mysterious beings of supernatural power, warlocks unlock magical effects both subtle and spectacular. Drawing on the ancient knowledge of beings such as fey nobles, demons, devils, hags, and alien entities of the Far Realm, warlocks piece together arcane secrets to bolster their own power.', '1d8', 1, 2, 0, '4d4', 10, 'gp'),
(12, 'Wizard', 'Clad in the silver robes that denote her station, an elf closes her eyes to shut out the distractions of the battlefield and begins her quiet chant. Fingers weaving in front of her, she completes her spell and launches a tiny bead of tire toward the enemy ranks, where it erupts into a conflagration that engulfs the soldiers. Checking and rechecking his work, a human scribes an intricate magic circle in chalk on the bare stone floor, then sprinkles powdered iron along every line and graceful curve. When the circle is complete, he drones a long incantation. A hole opens in space inside the circle, bringing a whiff of brimstone from the otherworldly plane beyond. Crouching on the floor in a dungeon intersection, a gnome tosses a handful of small bones inscribed with mystic symbols, muttering a few words of power over them. Closing his eyes to see the visions more clearly, he nods slowly, then opens his eyes and points down the passage to his left. Wizards are supreme magic-users, defined and united as a class by the spells they cast. Drawing on the subtle weave of magic that permeates the cosmos, wizards cast spells of explosive tire, arcing lightning, subtle deception, and brute-force mind control. Their magic conjures monsters from other planes of existence, glimpses the future, or turns slain foes into zombies. Their mightiest spells change one substance into another, call meteors down from the sky, or open portals to other worlds.', '1d6', 1, 2, 0, '4d4', 10, 'gp');
INSERT INTO `background` (`id`, `name`, `description`, `initial_equipment`, `languages`) VALUES
(1, 'Acolyte', 'You have spent your life in the service of a temple to a specific god or pantheon of gods. You act as an intermediary between the realm of the holy and the mortal world, performing sacred rites and offering sacrifices in order to conduct worshipers into the presence of the divine. You are not necessarily a cleric—performing sacred rites is not the same thing as channeling divine power. Choose a god, a pantheon of gods, or some other quasi-­--divine being from among those listed in \"Fantasy-­Historical Pantheons\" or those specified by your GM, and work with your GM to detail the nature of your religious service. Were you a lesser functionary in a temple, raised from childhood to assist the priests in the sacred rites? Or were you a high priest who suddenly experienced a call to serve your god in a different way? Perhaps you were the leader of a small cult outside of any established temple structure, or even an occult group that served a fiendish master that you now deny.', 'A holy symbol (a gift to you when you entered the priesthood), a prayer book or prayer wheel, 5 sticks of incense, vestments, a set of common clothes, and a belt pouch containing 15 gp', 2),
(2, 'Criminal', 'You are an experienced criminal with a history of breaking the law. You have spent a lot of time among other criminals and still have contacts within the criminal underworld. You\'re far closer than most people to the world of murder, theft, and violence that pervades the underbelly of civilization, and you have survived up to this point by flouting the rules and regulations of society.', 'A crowbar, a set of dark common clothes including a hood, and a belt pouch containing 15 gp', NULL),
(3, 'Folk Hero', 'You come from a humble social rank, but you are destined for so much more. Already the people of your home village regard you as their champion, and your destiny calls you to stand against the tyrants and monsters that threaten the common folk everywhere. ', 'A set of artisan’s tools (one of your choice), a shovel, an iron pot, a set of common clothes, and a belt pouch containing 10 gp', NULL),
(4, 'Noble', 'You understand wealth, power, and privilege. You carry a noble title, and your family owns land, collects taxes, and wields significant political influence. You might be a pampered aristocrat unfamiliar with work or discomfort, a former merchant just elevated to the nobility, or a disinherited scoundrel with a disproportionate sense of entitlement. Or you could be an honest, hard-working landowner who cares deeply about the people who live and work on your land, keenly aware of your responsibility to them. Work with your DM to come up with an appropriate title and determine how much authority that title carries. A noble title doesn\'t stand on its own—it\'s connected to an entire family, and whatever title you hold, you will pass it down to your own children. Not only do you need to determine your noble title, but you should also work with the DM to describe your family and their influence on you. Is your family old and established, or was your title only recently bestowed? How much influence do they wield, and over what area? What kind of reputation does your family have among the other aristocrats of the region? How do the common people regard them? What\'s your position in the family? Are you the heir to the head of the family? Have you already inherited the title? How do you feel about that responsibility? Or are you so far down the line of inheritance that no one cares what you do, as long as you don\'t embarrass the family? How does the head of your family feel about your adventuring career? Are you in your family\'s good graces, or shunned by the rest of your family? Does your family have a coat of arms? An insignia you might wear on a signet ring? Particular colors you wear all the time? An animal you regard as a symbol of your line or even a spiritual member of the family? These details help establish your family and your title as features of the world of the campaign.', 'A set of fine clothes, a signet ring, a scroll of pedigree, and a purse containing 25 gp', 1),
(5, 'Sage', 'You spent years learning the lore of the multiverse. You scoured manuscripts, studied scrolls, and listened to the greatest experts on the subjects that interest you. Your efforts have made you a master in your fields of study.', 'A bottle of black ink, a quill, a small knife, a letter from a dead colleague posing a question you have not yet been able to answer, a set of common clothes, and a belt pouch containing 10 gp', 2),
(6, 'Soldier', 'War has been your life for as long as you care to remember. You trained as a youth, studied the use of weapons and armor, learned basic survival techniques, including how to stay alive on the battlefield. You might have been part of a standing national army or a mercenary company, or perhaps a member of a local militia who rose to prominence during a recent war. When you choose this background, work with your DM to determine which military organization you were a part of, how far through its ranks you progressed, and what kind of experiences you had during your military career. Was it a standing army, a town guard, or a village militia? Or it might have been a noble\'s or merchant\'s private army, or a mercenary company.', 'An insignia of rank, a trophy taken from a fallen enemy (a dagger, broken blade, or piece of a banner), a set of bone dice or deck of cards, a set of common clothes, and a belt pouch containing 10 gp', NULL);
INSERT INTO `component` (`id`, `code`, `name`, `description`) VALUES
(1, 'V', 'Verbal', 'Most spells require the chanting of mystic words. The words themselves aren\'t the source of the spell\'s power; rather, the particular combination of sounds, with specific pitch and resonance, sets the threads of magic in motion. Thus, a character who is gagged or in an area of silence, such as one created by the silence spell, can\'t cast a spell with a verbal component.'),
(2, 'S', 'Somatic', 'Spellcasting gestures might include a forceful gesticulation or an intricate set of gestures. If a spell requires a somatic component, the caster must have free use of at least one hand to perform these gestures.'),
(3, 'M', 'Material', 'Casting some spells requires particular objects, specified in parentheses in the component entry. A character can use a component pouch or a spellcasting focus (found in “Equipment”) in place of the components specified for a spell. But if a cost is indicated for a component, a character must have that specific component before he or she can cast the spell. If a spell states that a material component is consumed by the spell, the caster must provide this component for each casting of the spell. A spellcaster must have a hand free to access a spell\'s material components—or to hold a spellcasting focus—but it can be the same hand that he or she uses to perform somatic components.');
